<h2>Hexagonal Orchards</h2><div id="problem_icons" class="noprint"><a href="minimal=351"><img src="images/icons/file_html.png" title="Show HTML problem content" class="icon"></a>&nbsp;<img src="images/icons/file_pdf_gs.png" alt="" title="Overview available for this problem" class="icon">&nbsp;<span class="tooltip"><img src="images/icons/info.png" class="icon"><span class="tooltiptext_right">Published on Saturday, 17th September 2011, 10:00 pm; Solved by 2897;<br>Difficulty rating: 25%</span></span></div><div id="problem_info"><h3>Problem 351</h3></div>
<div class="problem_content" role="problem">
<p>A <dfn>hexagonal orchard</dfn> of order $n$ is a triangular lattice made up of points within a regular hexagon with side $n$. The following is an example of a hexagonal orchard of order $5$:
</p>

<div align="center">
<img src="resources/images/0351_hexorchard.png?1678992052" class="dark_img" alt="0351_hexorchard.png"><br></div>

<p>
Highlighted in green are the points which are hidden from the center by a point closer to it. It can be seen that for a hexagonal orchard of order $5$, $30$ points are hidden from the center.
</p>

<p>
Let $H(n)$ be the number of points hidden from the center in a hexagonal orchard of order $n$.
</p>

<p>
$H(5) = 30$. $H(10) = 138$. $H(1\,000) = 1177848$.
</p>

<p>
Find $H(100\,000\,000)$.
</p>
</div><br>
<br>
